Anonymous Sun 03 Mar 2019 15:44:05 No.21652994 Report
Quoted By: >>21653116 >>21653230 >>21653298 >>21653415 >>21653823
>>21652577
I consider myself a bit of a Trek grognard, and I don't have a lot of hope for the Picard show. The simple truth is that Patrick Stewart is just an actor. The character of Picard was created by numerous people working on TNG, including Gene Roddenberry, who's influence it's hip to denigrate these days. Patrick Stewart himself is a great actor, but he's not a writer, and he's been the driving force behind turning Picard into more of an action hero type character. That entire bit with the offroad vehicle in Nemesis was there because Stewart wanted it to be there.

Now this man has an entire show devoted to him, which is being written by the same people behind Discovery. And Micheal Chabon, for some reason. He's a respected science fiction writer, though I couldn't get through The Yiddish Policemen's Union myself, but I was pretty young. Then again, I was already a Trek fan and reading PKD, so the fault has to at least be partially his.

Here's the problem: Good Trek was always the result of people wanting to make good Trek, as well as cutting edge television. Even in VOY and ENT they really tried to do new stuff, and they failed more than succeeded for a simple reason: They wanted to play it safe. ENT proved to be a scion for what was to come: It consciously purged itself of Star Trek style and even the Trek name. JJTrek and Discovery continue this legacy of producer-room safety. They reduce Trek down to a brand name, and then just make a regular movie/show. Nothing that sets it apart, so nothing that risks alienating the popcorn-munching normie audience. Because those are the people who are excited about DSC and the new Picard show: The people who watched Trek the way they watched Friends. Anonymous Sun 03 Mar 2019 16:57:13 No.21654139 Report

>>21653749
Suggest you use search engines. There is a huge community of preppers and survivalists with extensive lists of food and how to ensure your water supply and how to prepare whatever food you can find or salvage. It would take a long thread or several to get into the details. You might even want to spend some time in >>>/k/ and >>>/out/ to get started. There's probably general ongoing threads at all times on this topic and all the related peripherals.

If you're not familiar with the board culture (esp. >>>/k/ ), definitely do a good bit of lurking and reading before jumping into existing threads with n00b questions, let alone starting new threads.

In a nutshell, quite a number of foods can be preserved for long periods of time, so long as the preparation is done professionally and immaculately. In many cases it isn't the food itself that is as critical as the methods of preservation and storage, which are tailored to the expected methods to prepare that food when it comes time to eat it. Be clear in your mind the length of time you intend to include in your plot, also. A 30 year plan is vastly different from a 200 year plan. The extent & type of apocalypse, the recovery duration, how it's measured in generations are critical factors.

>recommend anything written by Cherryh
I fully endorse this recommendation. However, I do caution anyone interested enough to explore her work that her style changes drastically over 40 years and dozens of novels and dozens of shorts. Some is incredibly cerebral (The Faded Sun trilogy, Voyager in Night, Serpent's Reach) and other stuff (the Chanur saga) are more on the action end. And, she delves into high fantasy almost as much as hard science fiction. Personally, I love all her work one way or another and always recommend her, but not everything is to everyone's taste. And, on topic to this thread, she hasn't really written anything else like the Chanur saga. Most disappointingly, because it's pretty fucking awesome.

As far as our space human in a space cat crew .... I was trying hard not to spoil it. But, don't expect any porn or explicit scenes. His relationships are all implied due to the taboo nature of their pride culture, and the perspective of the stories: they are all from the cat women's viewpoints. You never get a scene from his first-person view, which is a brilliant bit of writing to pull off. All of the writing is from the perspectives of the crew members and how they are dealing with this alien that got dumped into their ship.

>>21655990
The "mirror universe" was never entirely serious. It started out as a "evil versions of the same characters" straight-up trope, in one episode of the original series. It was then explored a lot further in DS9, where they openly admitted they were having fun with it more than anything else, and there was an entire episode of ENT set there as well. (Also a bunch of non-cannon spinoff media.)

The practical upshot is that it sorta parallels the main universe For Unexplained Reasons, but beyond that, its history starts with Earth/Starfleet being an empire to which most other races are more-or-less subjects (while still sometimes serving in Starfleet, for, again, Unexplained Reasons). Then the crossover in TOS happens, and Mirror-Spock sets the Empire up to disintegrate, so by the time of Mirror-DS9, the other races are now dominating the humans. Lather, Rinse, Repeat, probably.

If you take it too seriously, you'll go mad.

Anonymous Sun 03 Mar 2019 19:06:34 No.21656424 Report
Quoted By:
>>21656107
>the original universe is based on communism

Gonna be honest here: I've always hated this perception of Star Trek. It's kind of flagrantly untrue, given that some of TOS' episode are highly critical of the Soviet Union indirectly (through the Klingons), and extremely directly in one rather ham-handed episode. It's the one where the literal communists are evil and about to be vanquished by strong, blonde, blue-eyed Americans.

The word you're looking for is "progressive". Star Trek was a socially progressive show, and openly spoke out against racism and in favor of sexual liberation, as well as other hippy values. One of those values was social equality, and that's what tends to get every earnest commie to call it pro-communist. But it says enough that the clearest marker of communism, a lack of currency, was really only added as a joke line in Star Trek IV, because it's not like we'd seen these people on a military/exploration vessel ever use money before. Money is actually mentioned in an episode of TAS, where they rescue a wealthy philanthropist who turns out to be a tentacle alien. In fact, money might actually be mentioned in the Harry Mudd episodes, though I can't recall. However, given that he peddles goods including to Federation citizens, one can assume an economy still exists.

More to the point, Trek never explains its supposed communism. Which means there is no communism. There is a vague sci-fi post-scarcity society. People viewing it as communist are more often than not projecting their own values onto the show. Which is fine, because the wide attraction of Trek is one of the things that makes it great, and I'd love for communists to strive for Trek rather than the USSR. But that's what it comes down to. Trek society is not communist. It's just close to the communist ideal. But the communist ideal itself is highly utopian, so that's no proof on its own.

You're putting a lot of thought into this at the moment. Well, the cup size lettering designations really aren't all about size or volume - they're catchall categories that encompass those things, but they're really meant to deal with just how wildly breast shapes vary. Really, no two pairs are the same, but there are general shape designations that help narrow it down. Based on a owman's shape, a "B" breast might be better suited to a C-cup bra, and so on. In fact, bras in the single B to D categories nearly have the same volume, they just better accommodate breasts based on two criteria: how prominent they are until they sag and bulge downward, and how round/large the bottom bulge (underboob) is. Personally, I felt she was more of a C because of the shape presented in artwork of her, but the differences in size aren't too noticeable. B-cup breasts tend to be more conical, though.
